00:26:54.230 --> 00:26:55.827
I'm definitely open.

00:26:55.827 --> 00:26:56.660
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:26:56.660 --> 00:26:59.060
AMANDA PHINGBODHIPAKKIYA: Sure.

00:26:59.060 --> 00:27:01.610
AUDIENCE: Can you share a little
more about your own journey

00:27:01.610 --> 00:27:06.260
from being a
neuroscientist to coming up

00:27:06.260 --> 00:27:10.370
with these works of art, and
how that took off, and turned

00:27:10.370 --> 00:27:13.220
into Beyond Curie as an
organization and everything?

00:27:13.220 --> 00:27:14.870
AMANDA PHINGBODHIPAKKIYA: Sure.

00:27:14.870 --> 00:27:19.430
So I realized that I was better
at communicating research

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:22.490
and communicating science than
actually doing the science,

00:27:22.490 --> 00:27:24.210
and I could make
more impact there.

00:27:24.210 --> 00:27:28.700
So I got my MFA at
Pratt, and after that, I

00:27:28.700 --> 00:27:31.790
bounced around different art
director and creative director

00:27:31.790 --> 00:27:32.720
positions.

00:27:32.720 --> 00:27:36.680
And then I got the
opportunity to do something

00:27:36.680 --> 00:27:40.400
called the TED Residency, which
is an incubator program where

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:45.160
you have some sort of idea worth
spreading that you apply with.

00:27:45.160 --> 00:27:47.630
Mine was that design can
shine a light on breakthroughs

00:27:47.630 --> 00:27:48.890
happening in science.

00:27:48.890 --> 00:27:52.660
And I actually incubated another
project, not Beyond Curie,

00:27:52.660 --> 00:27:53.860
there.

00:27:53.860 --> 00:27:56.330
It's a program that pairs
scientists and designers

00:27:56.330 --> 00:28:00.500
to cocreate works of art and
design that translate research.

00:28:00.500 --> 00:28:04.070
And we put out pop-up exhibits
all over the country and work

00:28:04.070 --> 00:28:07.430
with different institutions.

00:28:07.430 --> 00:28:10.040
Beyond Curie started
because I was

00:28:10.040 --> 00:28:13.760
trying to find a
way to give back

00:28:13.760 --> 00:28:16.700
after the election and support
causes that I believed in.

00:28:16.700 --> 00:28:19.850
And supporting women in
STEM is one of the ones

00:28:19.850 --> 00:28:21.860
that I believe in a lot.

00:28:21.860 --> 00:28:26.570
So I started it as a
little digital project

00:28:26.570 --> 00:28:28.290
that I wanted to put online.

00:28:28.290 --> 00:28:29.570
I thought, you know what?

00:28:29.570 --> 00:28:33.890
There are so many women that
people don't know about.

00:28:33.890 --> 00:28:35.510
Never heard their names before.

00:28:35.510 --> 00:28:37.343
They've probably heard
of their discoveries,

00:28:37.343 --> 00:28:38.990
but never knew that
women made them.

00:28:38.990 --> 00:28:42.410
So why don't we create a
format that's colorful,

00:28:42.410 --> 00:28:45.980
that's visually appealing so
that people's attentions are

00:28:45.980 --> 00:28:47.870
grabbed, and then we
can roll the stories

00:28:47.870 --> 00:28:50.090
into this experience?

00:28:50.090 --> 00:28:52.880
I did not expect for
it to be picked up

00:28:52.880 --> 00:28:56.000
by "Fast Company" and a bunch
of other different media

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:00.830
networks, which is kind of how
it grew to a global phenomenon.

00:29:00.830 --> 00:29:04.350
And I've just been continuing
to work on it, adding scientists

00:29:04.350 --> 00:29:04.850
to it.

00:29:08.270 --> 00:29:13.160
And we try very hard to go
into different countries

00:29:13.160 --> 00:29:15.410
and work with
different institutions

00:29:15.410 --> 00:29:16.880
to figure out
what's a way that we

00:29:16.880 --> 00:29:19.914
can bring Beyond Curie there.

00:29:19.914 --> 00:29:22.070
[LAUGHS] Thanks so
much for coming.

00:29:22.070 --> 00:29:25.720
